VEP 0039
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Written Submission by Professor Julian Roberts and Professor Mike Hough (VEP 0039)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Do you think sentence length is a valid proxy for deciding which prisoners get the right to vote?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is the best proxy for offence seriousness, and is preferable to a scheme which excludes certain prisoners, i
[normal].
[normal]e
[normal].,
[normal] those convicted of personal injury offences. Yet sentence length is still a poor tool to distinguish between prisoners in order to determine who should be disenfranchised. There is no point on the dimension of sentence length which provides a cut
[normal]-
[normal]off which is anything but arbitrary. The few correctional regimes that use sentence length – such as Canada – did so drawing upon an important
[normal] division of jurisdiction. Thus in Canada, federal prisoners – those serving two years or longer were disenfranchised, while provincial prisoners retained the vote. The federal provincial correctional bifurcation in jurisdiction split in Canada was important but has no 
[normal]equivalent 
[normal]counterpart in England and Wales. (In addition the disenfranchisement of federal prisoners 
[normal]in Canada 
[normal]was ultimately struck down on constitutional grounds
[normal] in R. v. Sauve)
[normal]. The closest alternative 
[normal]in England 
[normal]would be the Magistrate/ Crown court division but using this as the division would 
[normal]in our view 
[normal]be overbroad: federal prisoners in Canada represented only 
[normal]approximately 
[normal]3% of the 
[normal]total Canadian 
[normal]prison population; prisoners sentenced from the Crown Court represent a 
[normal]significantly
[normal] higher percentage of the total prisoner population.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our preferred approach would involve 
[normal]two 
[normal]steps:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What, if anything, is the 
[normal]significance of four
[normal] years and/or six months in the sentencing of criminals? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As noted, there is no significance; both are arbitrary thresholds.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]If you were to draw a line between serious and non-serious offences using sentence length, where would it be?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We would not draw the line, but one possibility would be to disenfranchise anyone sentenced to life imprisonment
[normal] on the grounds that they have committed a crime of such seriousness that the most severe penalty was warranted
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Can you think of an example where the sentence length approach could lead to an anomalous result? (For example, electoral fraud may result in a short sentence.)
[normal]Many cases heard at the Crown Court involve several counts, some relating to the same incident, some relating to completely separate incidents. If a threshold relating to sentence length is applied clear rules will be needed about the way in which total sentence is calculated. Clearly it would be anomalous to sum concurrent sentences, but 
[normal]more 
[normal]rational to do so for consecutive ones
[normal].
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It has been suggested by Liberty that the disenfranchisement of prisoners disproportionately impacts on ethnic minority communities. Is this correct?
[normal]Any groups that are less likely than others to secure sentencing discounts – eg for early guilty pleas or for expressing remorse will – other things being equal – be more likely to be disenfranchised. There is evidence that BME groups are 
[normal]less likely[bold] to enter early guilty pleas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]People nearing the end of their criminal careers – aiming to find a route out of crime – may by virtue of their long record actually be sentenced more heavily than those who are not trying to stop. This group may be over-represented.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]According to a note from the House of Commons Library,
[normal] 
[normal]approximately a quarter of those sentenced to less than four years have been convicted of a violent or sexual offence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Under what circumstances would someone convicted of these types of offences be sentenced to less than four years?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]As noted, we are of the view that 
[normal]all 
[normal]category-based exclusions are unwise. Why would you want to disenfranchise someone convicted of a crime of violence against a single individual 
[normal]but
[normal] not someone who has deprived dozens of elderly victims of their life savings 
[normal]yet
[normal] who is convicted of a property crime? Crime seriousness is a better yardstick
[normal] than offence category
[normal], but as we noted, there is no non-arbitrary cut
[normal]-
[normal]off. 
[normal]But to address the question directly, many offenders convicted of a crime of violence would be sentenced to much less than 4 years. For example, the guideline range for common assault carries a ceiling of 26 weeks.
[normal] Section 47 assaults are divided in the 
[normal]definitive sentencing 
[normal]guideline into 3 categories of seriousness, each with its own sentence range. The sentence range for the most serious category (1) is from 1-3 years.
[normal] The guidelines for less serious sexual assault involving an adult victim has starting points that span the custody threshold.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What proportion of convictions results in a custodial sentence?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]8% (98,047) of all offenders sentenced in 2012  (n = 1,229,827) get a custodial sen
[normal]tence
[normal]. This includes motoring and summary offences.
[normal]55,777
[normal] got a custodial sentence of 6 months or less (ie 4
[normal].5
[normal]%
[normal] of 1.2m
[normal])
[normal]89,289
[normal] got a custodial sentence of under four years (ie just over 7%)
[normal]8,758
[normal] got four years or more (or indeterminate)
[normal] – ie 0.7%
[normal]Of the, 1
[normal],229,827 sentenced in 2012, 1
[normal],139,263 are sentenced in magistrates courts and 90,564 are sentenced in the Crown Court (ie 7%)
[normal].
[normal]19,754 offenders out of the 1,160,776 offenders found guilty at magistrates courts are committed for sentence. (not quite 2%)
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]How many persons, convicted in the magistrates’ court of multiple offences, are given custodial sentences of more than six months in prison?
[normal]810 of the 1,132,866 offenders 
[normal]for whom
[normal] sentence length data 
[normal]are available 
[normal]in magistrates
[normal]’
[normal] courts 
[normal]we
[normal]re given sentences over 6 months.
