[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]For what sort of crimes are people likely to get a sentence of more than four years?
[normal](Assuming a not guilty plea): the most serious of domestic burglaries; street robbery involving a weapon); rape and serious sexual offences; GBH with intent; drug trafficking; homicides. 
[normal]People with previous convictions
[normal] 
[normal]are more likely to get longer sentences, other things being equal
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Or for under six months?
[normal] 
[normal]As above
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Can you give examples of criminal offences which fall on the threshold – e.g. for which sentences of, say, anything from three to six years, might be given? (i.e. a situation in which two people convicted of the same offence may get different sentences such that one is disenfranchised and the other is not)
[normal]The range
[normal] of sentences for apparently sim
[normal]ilar offences is wide. An early guilty plea will earn a 33% discount. 
[normal]Genuine 
[normal]remorse will get an additional reduction
[normal]. Aggravating factors can make a large difference: 
[normal]previous conv
[normal]i
[normal]ctions; 
[normal]young or elderly victims; premeditation
[normal] etc. In aggregate, these aggravating and mitigating factors can play as large a part in determining sentence as the charge.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Would considering disenfranchisement in terms of type of offence be more appropriate than focusing on length of sentence?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]No – for the reasons noted.
[normal] (with the exception of offences relating to election fraud and similar), 
[normal]&#xa0;
